Existing methods (CHEERS)

Anna Hutchinson

02/12/2019

CHEERS is a statistical method that accounts for subtle changes in the chromatin landscape to identify SNP enrichment across cell states.

Rather than converting annotations into a binary measure of present/absent at the SNP level (for which they found there were not many cell state specific changes in H3K27ac and ATAC-seq data), they model the peak properties.

Method

  1. Define a union of peak regions present across cell types and construct a matrix of normalised read counts.

  2. Calculate and rank specificity scores (the higher the rank score the more specific that peak is to that cell type). The peak specificity score is the normalised read count for that peak in that cell state divided by the square root of the sum of the squared normalised read counts for that peak across all cell states.

  3. Define SNP set as lead-SNPs and those with \(r^2>0.8\) and overlay these to the peaks.

  4. For the peaks that overlap the associated variants, calculate the mean specificity ranks and derive a P value representing the probability that SNP-peak overlap is random in that cell type.

Notes

  • They use their method to quantify SNP enrichment in various T/B cell states for various diseases. E.g. that IFN\(\beta\) is enriched for Systemic lupus erythematosus variants.

  • I like this method because the binary conversion of SNP-peak overlap commonly used seems to throw away lots of useful information in my opinion. E.g. do the peaks look different in different cell types/states.
